                                                       \n\nLarge gap, but very stable -> all CV improvements have led to LB improvements   \n(so far).                                                                       \n\nA lot of the public notebooks have leakage which leads to a smaller CV-LB gap,  \nbut is not as trustworthy.                                                      \n\nGaurav Rawat в–І1 2026-05-19\nfeel need to beat the 10 mark in cv to see marked improvements for my           \nexperiments . NN so far for me havent been doign that great maybe need to dive  \ndeep to design them better .                                                    \n\nDurga Kumari в–І-4 2026-05-19\nInteresting that v2.10 had slightly worse CV but matched LB almost perfectly.   \nUsually a good sign the model is generalizing more consistently rather than     \noptimizing fold-specific patterns.                                              \n\nHassan Gasim в–І-3 2026-05-20\nOutstanding progress so far. Regarding your note on Neural Networks             \nunderperforming: standard MLPs usually struggle with the spatial, sequential    \nnature of wellbore data compared to GBDTs. Since well logs are essentially      \ndepth-series data, have you considered a hybrid architecture? Implementing a    \n1D-CNN or a light Transformer backbone (like TabNet or FT-Transformer) grouped  \nby Well ID can capture the vertical stratigraphy layers much better than vanilla\nNNs. Looking forward to seeing how your NN experiments evolve once the          \narchitecture matches the geological domain!                                     \n\nshanzhong8 в–І1 2026-05-21\nCV 10.7  , LB 9.9                                                               \n\nGaurav Rawat 2026-05-22\nnice GBDT or NN .. was wondering how much folks are gettign with NN CV          \n\nshanzhong8 в–І2 2026-05-23\nTransformer                                                                     \n\nGaurav Rawat в–І1 2026-05-28\nAdding NN experiments now , just baselines now                                  \n\n вҖў CV 14.4 LB 17                                                                \n вҖў cv 8 lb 9                                                                    \n\nTucker Arrants в–І6 2026-05-29\nSingle model NN update:                                                         \n\nCV 8.5, LB 7.5                                                                  \n\nInference in 2 minutes lol                                                      \n\nGaurav Rawat в–І1 2026-05-29\nawesome ya I see NN infer like 2-3 mins .. :) maybe u framed the right Arch ..  \nmy cv not going down                                                            \n\nTucker Arrants в–І3 2026-06-08\nLB feels noisy to me. I often observe CV improvements of 0.7 feet or more,      \nleading to regressions in LB. I think some of my submissions were \"lucky\" e.g.  \nCV around 8 scoring 6.6 on LB.                                                  \n\nLatest results:                                                                 \n\nCV 6.7, LB 6.3 -> the \"lucky gap\" between CV and LB I previously observed (and  \ncan be observed on all the public notebooks) is starting to shrink. Think we    \nneed to be careful with LB here. Small number of public test set wells and heavy\ntail problemвҖҰ                                                                   \n\nRuby в–І5 2026-06-08\nrecent two experiments: CV 6.74 LB 6.48 CV 6.22 LB 7.18 I guess it is dominated \nby some bad cases                                                               \n\nJack 2026-06-08\nI'd be questioning where those CV improvements are coming from in relation to   \npast runs - might be insightful. I'm still trying to figure out what the heck   \nyou're doing for 2 mins inference.. well, that and orbit wars lol               \n\nGaurav Rawat 2026-06-08\nI dunno CV strategy needs to be alteare in one I got cv 7.4 but LB is like 9 .  \nmaybe need to have cv mixed with hard wells vs easy ones per fold or some custom\nway                                                                             \n\nJack 2026-06-08\nBut how would you define hard vs easy wells? I can think of some more direct    \nways of balancing folds                                                         \n\nYYH 2026-06-09\nAre the top-ranked solutions currently all based on physics models combined with\nmachine learning? It seems that some physics models have performed quite well in\nthis competition.It is easy to find numerous hard samples in the dataset that   \ncannot be predicted accurately by conventional physical models, which drives up \nthe RMSE score. I am currently working to address this issue.                   \n\n--- dwt discussion ---\nв•ӯв”Җ stage.1 : global search using linear prior tvt = linear(md,z) в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®\nв”Ӯ Author: hengck23 | Votes: 18 | Comments: 5 | Created: 2026-05-13             в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ sion/699326                                                                  в”Ӯ\nв•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ\n\nрҹҢҶ \ninbox%2F113660%2F1aabc18ee91163e6ba228c5e1db9b147%2FSelection_3505.png?generatio\nn=1778687376098048&alt=media                                                    \n\nNext post: stage.2 iterative local search for refinement                        \n\nв”Җв”Җ 5 Comments в”Җв”Җ\n\nhengck23 в–І1 2026-05-13\nрҹҢҶ \ninbox%2F113660%2Fc56ecec1fbf2e65293ed60b919a8d170%2FSelection_3507.png?generatio\nn=1778691758365065&alt=media                                                    \n\ninitalise with fitted line of md,z after PS and also using tvt_input. need to   \nthink of  a way to make it \"smooth\"                                             \n\nhengck23 в–І1 2026-05-13\nрҹҢҶ \ninbox%2F113660%2F56d68326c7bf5fb5347999c5889b0513%2FSelection_3508.png?generatio\nn=1778692190154785&alt=media                                                    \n\nрҹҢҶ \ninbox%2F113660%2F65ed9281146bfcc077582dd4d4e54495%2FSelection_3509.png?generatio\nn=1778692204746245&alt=media                                                    \n\nрҹҢҶ \ninbox%2F113660%2F528e2db812b1dec908fe6de6e42c9e74%2FSelection_3513.png?generatio\nn=1778693089162977&alt=media                                                    \n\ntop to bottom: typewell TVT-GR after PS, typewell TVT-GS, horizontal            \nMD-smoothedGS showing forward and reverse, horizontal MD-smoothedGS showing TVT \nas color, horizontal TVT-smoothedGS                                             \n\nhengck23 в–І3 2026-05-13\nрҹҢҶ \ninbox%2F113660%2Fdd4117e1392d8e76e50fec03ec6111df%2FSelection_3512.png?generatio\nn=1778692902303316&alt=media рҹҢҶ \ninbox%2F113660%2F3909dbc9cfac77444c5d3e6acfabc790%2FSelection_3511.png?generatio\nn=1778692880943488&alt=media gemini suggested this but i haven't tried:         \n\nhengck23 в–І4 2026-05-14\nthis is why prior (constraints) is important.                                   \n\nlower GR fitting doesn't mean lower T ** it is an inverse problem ! **          \n\nYou should learn the 2-parameter prior space using TVT RMSE, not GR RMSE.       \n\nрҹҢҶ \ninbox%2F113660%2F862c8e7dcb7c2c0594d4c769da63c3ca%2FSelection_3518.png?generatio\nn=1778728817525025&alt=media VT.                                                \n\nFranklin Gois 2026-06-03\n@hengck23 Thank you!                                                            \n\n--- alignment discussion maybe ---\nв•ӯв”Җ Duplicate type wells for different horizontal wells в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®\nв”Ӯ Author: RMorrison | Votes: 19 | Comments: 3 | Created: 2026-05-09            в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ sion/698449                                                                  в”Ӯ\nв•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ\n\nWhen doing a quick EDA, I noticed there are a few type well files that are      \nexactly the same but assigned to different horizontal wells. In some cases this \nmakes sense (wells that are oriented adjacent or on top of each other), but in  \nother cases the wells are quite distant from each other. Why would wells some   \ndistance apart be using exactly the same type well? Is this intentional?        \n\nHere are the well pairs with matching type wells, and a picture of how they are \noriented compared to other wells with different type wells.                     \n\nduplicate_groups = [ ['02e7fe5a', '10b89021', '3417285d', '6ae68655',           \n'7993a768', 'bc4381e2', 'ecdab904', 'f021b650', 'f49fdea3', 'f88ddb26'],        \n['071d7b45', '4463446c'], ['25939962', '8050c789'], ['2f8e53c3', '91db7070'],   \n['75cd5f11', 'be83e781'], ['7b38844c', 'ed6e6e54'], ['89f1085d', 'aed44918'],   \n['8b95d6d1', 'a2e8e7f6'], ['a4f989c2', 'd011f41b'], ['add9c322', 'cbe62450'],   \n['b977be4a', 'c908edd0'], ['cd7f1687', 'fcfcc902'], ['f321a31c', 'fa667be2'], ] \n\nв”Җв”Җ 3 Comments в”Җв”Җ\n\nPC Jimmmy 2026-05-10\nNice catch!                                                                     \n\nIgor Kuvaev в–І7 2026-05-10\nGood catch!                                                                     \n\nTypically typewell selection is a manual process, the geologist picks the one   \nthat is close to the lateral and available at the time. Wells in the project    \nwere drilled over 10 years and when you were drilling certain lateral the       \nclosest typewell (the one the is close now) could not be available.             \n\nAdditionally the geologist may take TVT GR data from the nearby interpreted     \nlateral to interpret the next lateral. Sometimes this helps a lot and this      \napproach is called \"pseudo-typewell\". Some of the typewells in the project are  \nactually \"pseudo-typewells\" - interpretations from nearby laterals drilled prior\nto the current one.                                                             \n\nMatthew Degtyar 2026-05-10\nVery clutch                                                                     \n\n--- online learning ---\nв•ӯв”Җ Can a single model achieve LB/CV below 10.0? в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®\nв”Ӯ Author: NobelK | Votes: 12 | Comments: 10 | Created: 2026-05-13              в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ sion/699207                                                                  в”Ӯ\nв•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ\n\nHi everyone,                                                                    \n\nI would like to ask whether it seems possible to achieve a score below 10.0 on  \nthe LB or local CV using a single model.                                        \n\nAt the moment, my single CatBoost model has plateaued. I am using mostly tabular\nfeatures with CatBoost, and my local CV and LB are no longer improving much     \nafter basic parameter tuning. I suspect that either my validation strategy or   \nfeature engineering may be the bottleneck, but I am not sure how to diagnose it.\n\nSince I am still a beginner, I would really appreciate any discussion or        \nexchange of ideas around this topic.                                            \n\nFor example, I am interested in hearing about:                                  \n\n вҖў whether people have seen single-model scores below 10.0                      \n вҖў whether CatBoost alone seems strong enough for this competition              \n вҖў which direction is more promising: feature engineering, validation design,   \n   post-processing, or ensembling                                               \n вҖў common mistakes that may cause a CatBoost baseline to get stuck              \n\nI am not asking for anyoneвҖҷs private solution, but I would be grateful for any  \ngeneral hints, observations, or advice that could help beginners understand     \nwhere to focus next.                                                            \n\nThanks in advance!                                                              \n\nв”Җв”Җ 10 Comments в”Җв”Җ\n\nYang Wei Hao в–І-1 2026-05-13\ni think it must do that                                                         \n\nTucker Arrants в–І2 2026-05-13\nOf course, the competition has only been live for a week. I have a simple LGB   \nthat scores 9.7 on the leaderboard - nothing fancy, just some feature           \nengineering. IвҖҷm sure the final scores will be much lower, maybe around 5 feet, \nbut it is hard to tell. Look at the leaderboard...there are some heavy hitters  \ncompeting here and it has only just begun - it's going to be a good one.        \n\nNobelK в–І1 2026-05-13\n9.7... That's fantastic.                                                        \n\nI still seem to lack the fundamentals, so I'll do my best to catch up.          \n\nThank you for the helpful information; let's both do our best.                  \n\nTom в–І1 2026-05-17\nCurrent GBDTs are definitely not a good solution for this challenge. Based on my\ncurrent EDA, there is still significant room for improvement. Ultimately, it    \ndepends on how the problem is reformulated. I'll post some new directions after \nI understand the data deeper.                                                   \n\nhengck23 в–І1 2026-05-17\nmy experment results: upper bound 3.5 (due to ambigous annotation). i think a   \ngood model is about 4.5. GBDTs is ok if the input is good.                      \n\nbut problem is not feature engineering, it is problem formulation. It is easier \nto work with CNN and transformer ( top k path query)                            \n\nNobelK в–І1 2026-05-17\nI'd like to use CNNs and transformers, but I lack the knowledge to build a model\nproperly.                                                                       \n\nI would be grateful if you could share any helpful resources or resources you   \nknow of.                                                                        \n\nAndrew Lukyanenko в–І3 2026-05-20\nThis is definitely possible. I got 9.463 with a single model.                   \n\nNobelK 2026-05-20\n9.463 with a single model!? That's amazing! I'm very interested in your         \napproach. I've run out of ideas right now...                                    \n\nVishal Kishore в–І4 2026-05-24\nYeah it is possible, I scored 8.8 with a single dl model approach only. Only    \nmatters how you formulate it in your model                                      \n\nNobelK 2026-05-24\nThat's a fantastic score!                                                       \n\nI have a basic question: what does it mean to \"formulate it in your model\"?     \n\n--- private update ---\nв•ӯв”Җ Private Test Update and Rescore в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®\nв”Ӯ Author: Ryan Holbrook | Votes: 14 | Comments: 4 | Created: 2026-06-11        в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus в”Ӯ\nв”Ӯ sion/707695                                                                  в”Ӯ\nв•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ\n\nHi everyone,                                                                    \n\nThere is an outlier well in the private test set that we've decided to exclude  \nfrom scoring. I will be beginning a rescore shortly. Since this only affects the\nprivate set, you won't notice any change in the leaderboard. And, since the data\nfor this well is still a part of the test set, the change shouldn't affect      \nsubmission runtimes either.                                                     \n\nBasically, this should be an invisible update except you might notice your      \nexisting submissions briefly have a score \"pending\" and this is why.            \n\nв”Җв”Җ 4 Comments в”Җв”Җ\n\nKanchana1990 в–І-1 2026-06-11\n@ryanholbrook 2 notebooks that lastly scored the best are know showing as an    \nerror, is it due to this? thanks for the info                                   \n\nMasonLeSaint 2026-06-12\nрҹҢҶ \ninbox%2F32853119%2F073129b206a03ab7aa0f129a4436c679%2FScreenshot%202026-06-12%20\n142948.png?generation=1781249429361561&alt=media рҹҢҶ \ninbox%2F32853119%2Fefcbf16e521c218bf6ea8b3d7a303c7f%2FScreenshot%202026-06-12%20\n142929.png?generation=1781249461295848&alt=media Hi @ryanholbrook My submitted n\nis still run. So could you explain the way of scoring phase work?               \n\nErtuДҹrul Demir 2026-06-12\nSame here my best scoring got an error, submit exact same notebook and it       \nworked, weird...                                                                \n\nRyan Holbrook в–І1 2026-06-12\nApologies for the trouble. I've alerted the team. Have you noticed the error    \nrecur since yesterday?                                                          \n\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
